\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field of opto-acoustics shot into prominence in 2006, when three independent
 research groups achieved significant damping (i.e.
 suppression) of acoustic modes of a mechanical resonator placed within
 an optical cavity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arcizet2006,Gigan2006,Kleckner2006"

\end_inset

.
 This was achieved by exploiting the small radiation pressure force that
 electromagnetic radiation exerts upon matter.
 There is promise that such “opto-acoustic” cavities could achieve damping
 so strong that one or more acoustic modes could be “cooled” to the quantum
 ground state.
 To do this would require an energy reduction factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{5}$
\end_inset

 from the thermal equilibrium value.
 If this feat is achieved, a cornucopia of related quantum mechanical experiment
s could be realised: the generation of quantum superpositions of a macroscopic
 object 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marshall2003"

\end_inset

; opto-acoustic entanglement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vitali2007"

\end_inset

; and experiments exploring the transition from the quantum regime to the
 classical world 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bose1999"

\end_inset

.
 These possibilities provide significant motivation to overcome the limits
 of current opto-acoustic cavities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whilst current designs could theoretically reach the quantum ground state
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marquardt2007"

\end_inset

, they face a host of technical challenges which are not easily overcome.
 Current designs can already damp a mode to within a factor of 30 away from
 the quantum ground state, but they are already pushing the limits of the
 technique, so realising further damping is very difficult.
 All opto-acoustic cavities built to date can be considered to rely upon
 a two-mode interaction, between the fundamental optical mode of the cavity
 and an acoustic mode of a mechanical resonator.
 The damping does not arrive from radiation pressure alone, but rather from
 time dependence of the radiation pressure force and corresponding back-action
 effects.
 This force can be characterised as that of an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optical spring
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with spring constant 
\begin_inset Formula $k(I,\,\Delta\omega)$
\end_inset

, which has a real and an imaginary component.
 The optical spring depends mainly upon the intracavity power 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and the detuning of the cavity away from resonance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The real part of this quantity is known as the optical rigidity and is
 analogous to the spring constant 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of a physical spring.
 It is the imaginary part of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(I,\,\Delta\omega)$
\end_inset

 which gives rise to the viscous damping force which is used to damp the
 acoustic mode.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the cavity is at resonance, then both the real and imaginary components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(I,\,\Delta\omega)$
\end_inset

 are zero, so there is no net damping or rigidity.
 Only when the cavity is detuned can one achieve radiation pressure damping.
 Detuning has the side effect that the intracavity power drops significantly.
 To compensate, the cavity must be pumped by higher laser power and as a
 result laser phase noise is increased.
 This noise acts to amplify the acoustic mode and this forms the main limiting
 factor associated with these simple opto-acoustic cavities.
 
\end_layout

