\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, if the imaginary part of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is negative, the acoustic mode is amplified and the opto-acoustic system
 can become unstable.
 This can be described as a type of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parametric instability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For several years, physicists at the University of Western Australia (UWA)
 have been working on a related phenonemon - parametric instabilities in
 gravitational wave interferometers.
 This was first predicted in 2001 by Braginsky, who posited that opto-acoustic
 coupling could cause exponential amplification of acoustic modes in the
 test masses of gravitational interferometers, jeopardising their operation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Braginsky2001"

\end_inset

.
 This parametric instability arises not from a two-mode interaction like
 those discussed above, but a three-mode interaction between two optical
 modes and one acoustic mode.
 This was initially dismissed as a cause for concern by most, as it requires
 specific conditions to be met.
 Further research and simulations conducted by the UWA group however, show
 that parametric instability is indeed probable in gravitational wave detectors
 such as AdvLIGO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhao2005"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UWA group has much experience in the control of parametric interactions
 and forced oscillations: they have investigated parametric back-action
 effects in sapphire transducers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cuthbertson1997"

\end_inset

; achieved mode damping in a resonant niobium bar gravitational wave detector
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blair1995"

\end_inset

; and characterised the oscillations in sapphire test masses used within
 gravitational interferometers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tobar1993"

\end_inset

.
 More recently, the UWA group has demonstrated a three-mode interaction
 in a 77m long Fabry-Perot cavity, between two optical modes and one acoustic
 mode 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhao2007,Zhao2008"

\end_inset

.
 Whilst this experiment was initially designed to show the existence of
 parametric instabilities in large scale interferometers, a new configuration
 was found that could theoretically be used to achieve damping of the acoustic
 mode.
 It was also found that this three-mode configuration could be achieved
 in a simple tabletop experiment.
 This led to the invention of what has been dubbed an 
\emph on
Opto-Acoustic Parametric Amplifier
\emph default
 (OAPA), which is discussed in detail in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:OAPAs"

\end_inset

 and also in the article by Miao et al., which is an introduction to the
 concept 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Miao2008"

\end_inset

.
 Essentially, OAPAs are opto-acoustic cavities which utilise a three-mode
 interaction.
 Theoretical calculations, even if conservative, show that OAPAs promise
 to enable stronger damping than is possible with a two-mode approach, as
 well as the possibility of realising three-mode parametric instability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The OAPA requires systems with pairs of optical modes, and an acoustic mode
 that matches the shape of the optical modes.
 Thus a necessary precursor to the construction of an OAPA is characterising
 the acoustic modes of the resonator to be used.
 Specifically, one must know its resonant frequencies, their corresponding
 mode shapes and their intrinsic quality factors.
 After this is known, an opto-acoustic cavity can be constructed to couple
 the acoustic mode to the optical modes of the cavity.
 In this report, two candidate resonators are characterised, which are shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:microtechno"

\end_inset

.
 The first characterisation scheme was realised experimentally at the Laboratoir
e Kastler Brossel (LKB) in Paris; the second at UWA in Perth.
 These are discussed in Chapters 3 and 4, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LKB group has significant experience in two-mode damping experiments
 and were the first to show that radiation pressure force could be used
 to damp the movement of a mirror 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cohadon1999"

\end_inset

.
 In 2006, they published an article in Nature describing an experimental
 setup that achieved strong damping with a two-mode interaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arcizet2006"

\end_inset

.
 Two other research groups, who had achieved similar results independently,
 published articles in the same issue of Nature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gigan2006,Kleckner2006"

\end_inset

.
 As mentioned earlier, the simultaneous publication of these articles acted
 to illuminate the new frontier of opto-acoustics.
 Currently, the LKB group are collaborating with UWA to construct an OAPA
 with which to achieve mode damping.
 There is much promise that an OAPA constructed by these two groups could
 achieve damping down to the quantum ground state, which would be a momentous
 achievement and usher in a new regime of experiments to investigate transitions
 between the classical and quantum worlds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Opto-Acoustic Parametric Amplifiers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:OAPAs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motivation for this report is to examine whether the two resonators
 discussed are suitable candidates for use in OAPAs.
 To elucidate which characteristics of the resonators are important, this
 section provides a brief overview of the OAPA.
 The OAPA is simply an opto-acoustic cavity which utilises the coupling
 of two different optical modes to the acoustic mode of a resonator, in
 a three-mode interaction.
 The OAPA achieves this coupling by radiation pressure that arrives from
 the beating between two or more optical modes resonant within the cavity.
 If the beat frequency between these two modes is resonant with the frequency
 of an acoustic mode, a strong radiation pressure force will arise.
 Depending on the sign of this force, it can either damp or amplify the
 vibrational amplitude of the acoustic mode.
 This can be seen as a simple scattering process in which energy is transferred
 from a photon (optical mode), to a phonon (acoustic mode), or vice versa.
 When a phonon of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 annihilates with a photon of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, it imparts its energy to the photon, which increases the photon's frequency
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}=\omega_{1}+\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, a photon of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 can scatter into a photon of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 and phonon of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=\Omega_{2}+\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 These are commonly known as the 
\emph on
Anti-Stokes process
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Stokes process 
\emph default
respectively and are shown diagramatically in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Para Interaction-2"

\end_inset


\emph on
.
\end_layout

