\begin_layout Standard
It is informative to view the Stokes and Anti-Stokes from a formal quantum
 mechanical perspective; which is studied in more detail in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:QO description"

\end_inset

.
 We can view the Stokes process as being equivalent to a system of photons
 and phonons acted on by creation and annihilation operators
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{a}_{k}\hat{b}_{q}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k'}^{\dagger}\left|n_{k},n_{k'},n_{q}\right\rangle =\sqrt{n_{k'}\left(n_{q}+1\right)\left(n_{k}+1\right)}\left|n_{k}-1,n_{k'}+1,n_{q}+1\right\rangle .\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k'}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 represents creation of a new photon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{k'}=\hbar\omega_{k}-\hbar\omega_{q}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{q}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 represents the creation of a phonon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{q}$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}$
\end_inset

 represents the destruction of the original photon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{k}.$
\end_inset

 Consequently the number of photons 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k'}$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $k'$
\end_inset

 increases by 1, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decreases by 1 and the number of phonons 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}$
\end_inset

 in with wavevector 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 also increases by 1.
 Similarly, for the Anti-Stokes process
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{a}_{k}\hat{b}_{q}\hat{a}_{k''}^{\dagger}\left|n_{k},n_{k'},n_{q}\right\rangle =\sqrt{n_{k'}n_{q}\left(n_{k}+1\right)}\left|n_{k}-1,n_{k''}+1,n_{q}-1\right\rangle ,\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k'}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 represents creation of a new photon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{k''}=\hbar\omega_{k}+\hbar\omega_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 These two processes represent the quantum picture for the opto-acoustic
 parametric interactions discussed in this thesis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum physics asserts that there is a minimum possible energy associated
 with each acoustic mode, known as the quantum ground state.
 At this energy, the phonon number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}=0$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 As stated previously, this state has never been attained in a macroscopic
 system, and there is promise that it may be possible via parametric mode
 damping in an OAPA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marshall2003,Miao2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The OAPA can be seen as a device with which to control these interactions,
 to either damp or amplify the acoustic mode of a resonator by altering
 its phonon number.
 The OAPA differs from previously constructed opto-acoustic cavities as
 the created photons are of a different optical mode to those annihilated.
 As a result, it has some unique properties that set it apart from two-mode
 based schemes.
 In an OAPA detuning is not required, so the laser light injected into the
 cavity is resonant.
 This means much higher intracavity power is achieved, so far lower laser
 pumping powers are required.
 They are also more immune to laser phase noise, which is enhanced in the
 offset pumping required for two mode systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall effects of parametric interactions upon the acoustic vibrations
 of the mechanical component of an OAPA can be described by a quantity known
 as 
\emph on
parametric gain
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

, which is defined as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}=\pm\frac{4I_{pump}Q_{0}Q_{1}Q_{m}\Lambda}{mcL\omega_{m}^{2}}.\label{eq:parametric gain}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This quantity is explained in detail by Miao et al.
 and was first introduced by Braginsky in 2001 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Miao2008,Braginsky2001"

\end_inset

.
 Briefly, its magnitude depends upon the quality factors of the acoustic
 and optical modes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{m}$
\end_inset

; the resonator mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

; the acoustic mode frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}$
\end_inset

; the laser pumping power, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{pump}$
\end_inset

; and, how well the these modes overlap spatially, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
 The sign of the gain depends upon whether the Stokes (+) or Anti-Stokes
 (-) mode is resonant within the optical cavity.
 It is thus highly important to have knowledge of the resonant frequencies,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-factors and mode shapes of the acoustic modes of the resonator to be used
 in an OAPA, to ensure large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 can be reached.
 Thus, resonator characterisation is essential.
 
\end_layout

