\begin_layout Standard
The overall effects of an OAPA upon the acoustic mode depend upon the sign
 and magnitude of the parametric gain.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}>1$
\end_inset

, then the energy imparted by the parametric amplification is greater than
 the decay rate of the acoustic mode.
 If this happens, then the amplitude of the acoustic mode will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ring-up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 exponentially, in which case parametric instability occurs.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}<0$
\end_inset

, the acoustic mode will be suppressed in what is commonly known as 
\emph on
cooling
\emph default
.
 As temperature is related to the acoustic vibrations of a system by the
 fluctuation-dissipation theorem (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Fluctuation-dissipation-theorem"

\end_inset

), this mode damping is analogous to changing the mode's effective temperature.
 In reality, this process does little to drop the actual temperature of
 a microresonator, so the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cooling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bears misleading semantic connotations.
 As such, the use of this term has been avoided throughout this report.
